Feels a bit like hyperobjects mixed with constructivist theory gone wild https://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/hyperobjects

The Snowcrash idea of memetic viruses is also related imo. My MA thesis was on climate change and the Syrian Civil War, and the climate change part (as a meme, not a cause) fit into this
Hyperobjects are phenomenon given meaning (and that also challenge that meaning) whereas this hyperstition feels like its purely cultural and constructed.

Climate change is the one most frequently cited because it exists across so many time scales, and is basically both detectable but bordering on unknowable because of the scope. Good post might be this: https://www.wired.com/story/timothy-morton-hyperobjects-all-the-way-down/
I actually kind of think the network/web 123 phenomenon fits into this model, b/c there’s something about networked thought/collab/creation that fits the locally observable/globally unknowable frame.

Maybe more understanding (or observing) a microcosm without really comprehending or being able to witness the whole of something. The 3 body problem series is allll hyberobjects, for example: threats/challenges so vast but non-specific (like the dark forest idea) that almost no one can really engage with the whole.
It is glorious. Have fun!
